sentences: Jessica Cottis (born 13 December 1979, Sale, Victoria, Australia) is an Australian-British conductor.
She is currently artistic director and chief conductor of the Canberra Symphony Orchestra.
She was a prize winner in the 2000 Australian Young Performers' Competition and made her European debut as an organist at London's Westminster Cathedral the next year.
She was a prize winner in the 2000 Australian Young Performers' Competition and made her European debut as an organist at London's Westminster Cathedral the next year.
Cottis read law at the University of London and in 2006 began conducting studies at the Royal Academy of Music where her teachers included Colin Metters and Sir Colin Davis.
She graduated from the Royal Academy of Music in 2009, with distinction, and was appointed RAM Manson Fellow in Composition.
She was made an Associate of the Royal Academy of Music in 2015.

Upon graduation from the Royal Academy of Music, in September 2009, she became the first Postgraduate Conducting Fellow of the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland and was appointed assistant conductor with the BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra, where her mentors included Donald Runnicles.
She served 2 years in the post.
In 2012, after an extensive search process, the Sydney Symphony Orchestra appointed Cottis its assistant conductor, and she held this post for 2 years.
In 2012, after an extensive search process, the Sydney Symphony Orchestra appointed Cottis its assistant conductor, and she held this post for 2 years.
She worked closely with the orchestra's then-chief conductor, Vladimir Ashkenazy, and conducted the orchestra in over 30 concerts a year.
In 2014, Cottis was appointed principal conductor of the Glasgow New Music Expedition, where she curated notable projects alongside visual artists and filmmakers.
In 2014, Cottis became a visiting professor in conducting at the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland.
Cottis conducted her first commercial recording, Gallipoli Symphony, in 2015, a tri-nation project of cultural diplomacy between Australia, New Zealand and Turkey, for ABC Classics.
In 2021, Cottis became artistic director and chief conductor of the Canberra Symphony Orchestra, the first female conductor to hold the posts.
